    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-09-24T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-09-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="537"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d537">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">312.93/182</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chinese Chargé</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Yung Kwai</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Memorandum</hi>
                </p>
                <p>During the last few years internal disorders in Mexico have been such as to
                    render life and property unsafe for Chinese citizens in many parts of that
                    country.</p>
                <pb facs="0662" n="577" xml:id="pg_577"/>
                <p>At the request of the Chinese Legation, the Department of State has been good
                    enough to send instructions to American Consular officers in various parts of
                    Mexico to use their good offices to protect Chinese citizens in time of
                        need.<note n="55" xml:id="d537fn55">See <ref target="frus1913#pg_916">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1913, pp. 916</ref>–<ref
                            target="frus1913#pg_923">923</ref>; <ref target="frus1914#pg_896">1914,
                            pp. 896</ref>–<ref target="frus1914#pg_900">900</ref>; <ref
                            target="frus1915#pg_1087">1915, pp. 1087</ref>–<ref
                            target="frus1915#pg_1096">1096</ref>; <ref target="frus1916#pg_795"
                            >1916, pp. 795</ref>–<ref target="frus1916#pg_797">797</ref>; and <ref
                            target="frus1917#pg_1088">1917, pp. 1088</ref>–<ref
                            target="frus1917#pg_1092">1092</ref>.</note> In recent months the
                    situation in Mexico seems to have grown worse, and many outrages have been
                    committed upon Chinese residents.</p>
                <p>In pursuance of instructions from his Government the Chinese Chargé d’Affaires
                    begs to request that fresh instructions be sent to American Consular officers in
                    Mexico to afford protection to Chinese citizens in case of necessity; and he
                    desires to thank the Department in advance for its kind compliance with his
                    request.</p>
                <closer>
                    <dateline rendition="#left">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-09-24">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 24, 1919</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </closer>
            </div>
